column4087: instructionLines:["To hydrate the grains: The first time you use the dehydrated grains (or if they have been stored for an extended period of time)
column4088: they need to be hydrated to become active."
column4089: In a small pan, heat 2 cups of the water over medium-high heat to just boiling.
column4090: Place 1/4 cup of the raw sugar in a 1-quart glass jar and cover with the hot water.
column4091: Stir to thoroughly dissolve the sugar.
column4092: Add enough room-temperature water to bring the level of the liquid to the shoulder of the jar.
column4093: Cool the mixture to room temperature and then add the grains.
column4094: Cover the opening with fine-weave cheesecloth or a kitchen towel and secure with a rubber band.
column4095: Allow the mixture to sit at room temperature for 3 to 4 days until the grains are plump.
column4096: You are taking a risk if you let them sit any longer than 5 days, as the grains may start to lose their potency from lack of food (sugar).
column4097: To make the kefir: In a small pan, heat 2 more cups of the water over medium-high heat to just boiling.
column4098: Divide the remaining 1/2 cup sugar between two 1-quart glass jars and cover evenly with the hot water.
column4099: Stir to thoroughly dissolve the sugar.
column4100: Add enough room-temperature water to bring the level of the liquid to the shoulder of the jar.
column4101: Cool the mixture to room temperature, and then add equal amounts of the loose plump grains in each jar.
column4102: Cover the jar opening with fine-weave cheesecloth or a kitchen towel and secure with a rubber band.
column4103: Allow the mixture to sit at room temperature for 24 to 48 hours, depending on the level of sweetness you want.
column4104: Shorter time will result in a sweeter kefir; longer will be less so.
column4106: About 12 hours before you are ready to strain the kefir, start a new batch of sugar water to prepare for the next batch of kefir.
column4107: This sugar water will need to be ready to receive the grains once you have strained the kefir.
column4108: Once it has reached the desired level of sweetness, use a dedicated fine-mesh nylon strainer to strain off the liquid into a spouted glass measuring vessel.
column4109: Using a funnel, fill two 1-liter swing-top bottles.
column4110: Place the captured grains in the new batch of sugar water to store.
column4111: Secure the caps on the bottles and leave at room temperature until ready to consume.
column4112: In a day or so, tiny bubbles of carbonation will appear.
column4113: This will increase as time passes and if you add fruit to the kefir.
column4114: Water kefir does not need to be refrigerated unless you want it chilled.
column4115: It’s best to consume within 10 days after opening a bottle.
column4116: Unused grains can be fed and stored, covered, in sugar water (1/4 cup sugar to 1 quart water), and refrigerated for up to 2 weeks.
column4117: Bring the mixture to room temperature before using the grains for a new batch of kefir.
column4118: For longer periods of storage, the grains should be laid out to dehydrate, stored in an airtight container, and refrigerated.
column4119: This process returns the grains to their original state.
column4120: Note: Kefir grains require minerals to thrive.
column4121: Hard, mineral-rich water such as well water or spring water is best.
column4122: Do not use filtered water because too many of the minerals will have been removed.
column4123: If using tap water, first bring it to a boil to remove any possible chlorine, and then cool it to room temperature before using.
column4124: Supplementing with Trace Mineral Drops (1/8 teaspoon per quart of water) is a good security measure.
column4125: These can be purchased from the same source as your grains.]
